# Cursor rules — Ember & Iron storefront
#
# The canonical guide is AGENTS.md. Read it first and follow it.
# This file is a short pointer so Cursor picks up the same rules.

You are working on the **Ember & Iron** BBQ e‑commerce storefront.

CANONICAL DOCS (read before editing):
- AGENTS.md       → rules, architecture, conventions, gotchas (source of truth)
- ARCHITECTURE.md → how the single HTML file is structured internally
- BRAND.md        → product catalog, brand voice, palette, SEO keywords
- README.md       → overview + path to production

NON‑NEGOTIABLE RULES:
1. Vanilla only — no frameworks, no build step, no npm, no CSS libraries.
2. All app code lives in `index.html` (the only exception is
   `product-images.js`, which holds base64 image data).
3. It is a client‑side SPA: "pages" are `.view` divs toggled by `switchView()`
   with History‑API routing (`ROUTES`). There is no server.
4. Commerce is simulated (payment, orders, email, inventory, analytics are
   front‑end stubs). Production target is headless Shopify.
5. Theme is token‑driven ("cast‑iron steel", Figtree font). Use the `:root` CSS
   custom properties — never hard‑code a hex colour.
6. Product image tiles MUST stay light (`--media`): the line‑art is dark ink and
   photos use `mix-blend-mode: multiply`, so a dark tile hides them.
7. Don't regress accessibility, WCAG‑AA contrast, or the JSON‑LD structured data.
8. The customer‑account/login feature was removed — the store is guest‑only.
   Don't reintroduce it unless asked.

WORKFLOW:
- The HTML is ~240 KB — search/locate before editing; make small, exact edits.
- After any change (especially scripted edits to the `products` array or JSON‑LD),
  serve over HTTP and check the browser console — one syntax error blanks the app.
- Keep the on‑page FAQ and the FAQPage JSON‑LD in sync.
- Product names contain `"` — escape them in HTML attributes and JSON.
